When trying to use SimDiff 4 (for example) as an external diff tool, it was configured as the following:
* External Diff Tool: Custom
* Diff Command: {{C:\Program Files\EnSoft\SimDiff4\simdiff4.exe}}
* Arguments: {{-leftModel $LOCAL -rightModel REMOTE}}

When clicking "External Diff", nothing happens. 

With these parameters, the config file looks like this:
{noformat}
[difftool "sourcetree"]
cmd = 'c:/Program Files/EnSoft/SimDiff 4/simdiff4.exe -leftModel $LOCAL -rightModel $REMOTE' \"$LOCAL\" \"$REMOTE\"
{noformat}
Shouldn't it become the following instead?
{noformat}
cmd = 'c:/Program Files/EnSoft/SimDiff 4/simdiff4.exe' -leftModel $LOCAL -rightModel $REMOTE
{noformat}

Adding the parameters in {{.gitconfig}} manually worked fine.

At my organization we often prepend our commit messages with the key or keys of the JIRA issue(s) the commit addresses.  Something like this if the commit addresses one issue...

{noformat}[MYJIRAPROJECT-123]: My commit message.{noformat}

Or this if the commit addresses multiple issues...

{noformat}[MYJIRAPROJECT-123, MYJIRAPROJECT-456, SOMEOTHERJIRAPROJECT-789]: My other commit message.{noformat}

We should probably be entering this issue data in the commit message in a more easily parsed format, like a JSON array...
{noformat}
    [
        "MYJIRAPROJECT-123",
        "MYJIRAPROJECT-456",
        "SOMEOTHERJIRAPROJECT-789"
    ]
{noformat}
It would be nice if I could give SourceTree the address of my JIRA server and then SourceTree could provide a drop down list of available issues when I make my commit.  SourceTree would then automatically prepend my commit message with a JSON string like the one above.

There are a lot of things that could be done with this information, from SourceTree and from JIRA.

SourceTree could provide a hyperlink to the JIRA issues that were linked to by the commit.  When the commit was pushed to master a JIRA hook could be implemented that would automatically create a hyperlink in any JIRA issues mentioned in the commit's JSON string.  When clicked the hyperlink would cause SourceTree to open and navigate directly to the commit in question.

Maybe I'm missing something, but I find no easy or obvious way to do these actions in one command:
 - remove non-tracked files from the working directory;
 - checkout a specific revision;

If I compare with TortoiseHg, the action would be "purge" (which if my memory is correct is an optional extension of mercurial).
I often find useful to just clear the whole working directory from anything but the content of the checkout, with no untracked files and no uncommited changes.

For now I found ways to do something equivalent in SourceTree but the simplest way is to:
 1. delete manually the content of the working directory but the .git directory;
 2. use checkout in SourceTree but on a previous revision (because SourceTree don't allow re-checkouting the current revision if it's the head???) with the box checked for ignoring changes;
 3. checkout again but the last revision this time.

When checking out a new branch from a remote, there should be an option to force/override the current local branch. This would allow a fresh copy without pull/rebase.

Without it, SourceTree results in an error:
{code}
git -c diff.mnemonicprefix=false -c core.quotepath=false checkout -b develop --track origin/develop
fatal: A branch named 'develop' already exists.
{code}

With a force option, the Git command would be:
{code}
git.exe checkout -f  -B develop remotes/origin/develop
{code}

After installing SourceTree, I was met with a dialogue window stating that it couldn't find Git on my system. It gave me 3 ways to deal with it.

The window also had an button for exiting SourceTree however it says:
{quote}
E_xit SourceTree
{quote}
